# Git policy

## Jarvis identity (all git/GitHub interactions)

Every commit, push, fetch, and `gh` call uses the **Jarvis** bot account — never host credentials or Cursor/IDE defaults.

- **Author + committer:** `Jarvis` / `lhrs_jarvis@users.noreply.github.com` (`GIT_AUTHOR_NAME`, `GIT_AUTHOR_EMAIL` in `.env`).
- **Never** attribute commits to Cursor, Cursor Agent, Composer, or any tool/IDE name.
- **Never** add `Co-authored-by:` trailers for Cursor, Cursor Agent, or similar.
- **SSH:** `.secrets/jarvis_ed25519` (`GITHUB_SSH_KEY_PATH`). Ignore host `~/.gitconfig` and ssh-agent:

```bash
GIT_CONFIG_GLOBAL=/dev/null GIT_CONFIG_NOSYSTEM=1 \
GIT_AUTHOR_NAME=Jarvis GIT_COMMITTER_NAME=Jarvis \
GIT_AUTHOR_EMAIL=lhrs_jarvis@users.noreply.github.com \
GIT_COMMITTER_EMAIL=lhrs_jarvis@users.noreply.github.com \
GIT_SSH_COMMAND="ssh -i ./.secrets/jarvis_ed25519 -o IdentitiesOnly=yes -o IdentityAgent=none -F /dev/null" \
git …
```

- **`gh` / GitHub API:** `GITHUB_PAT` (Jarvis bot PAT), not personal tokens.
- Do not pass `git commit --author=…` with a non-Jarvis identity.

## Push / branch policy

- **Never push** (`git push`, `gh` commands that push, force-push, etc.) unless the user **explicitly** asks in the current request or a standing user rule.
- If a workflow would normally push (e.g. opening a PR), stop at commit or tell the user what to push — do not push on your own.
- **Pull and branch switches are allowed** when useful: `git pull`, `git fetch`, `git checkout`, `git switch`, creating local branches, etc. Use judgment; no need to ask first.
- **Commits** still follow the existing rule: only commit when the user explicitly asks.
